Deleted User 2024-10-02 11:18 PM
my big boy tips are think mostly about what transmission you want and what fuel type, those are massive. in the UK plug in electric is the cheapest, whereas petrol is a little bit more expensive with diesel being the highest priced. however, don’t let it put you off. think about space, how comfortable will you be driving the car? you need to sit and think, can i see out of the front window? is my seat adjustable? do my feet sit comfortably in my footwell? think about any previous experience from sitting in the car, what did you like, what did you hate. weighing all that up is great. i went for a big SUV because i’m small, but i have a disability. i really need to focus on comfort, i need to be comfortable driving otherwise i’ll have a bad time and won’t want to drive in the first place THEN once you’ve shortlisted cars from that, you can start thinking about extras. apple carplay, heated steering wheel, heated seats, air con, driver assist features, those are the luxuries of car ownership. my honeybee car has all the fancy features but that’s because it’s a sports car and its brand spanking new (edited)

An E7 Tariff, otherwise known as Economy 7, makes it so your electric prices are much cheaper at night when you’d charge the car but slightly higher during the day to compensate for the good rates you get at night

Crypt𝕆𝕨𝕝ℂ𝕚𝕥𝕪𝕄ℙ𝟛 2024-10-05 11:27 AM
so due to the nature of how I made this thing, it's actually kinda possible to play the longer snippet here's how it basically works since i think you're technical enough to understand: 1. I split audio files in 1 sec snippet with audacity (there's a tool that auto insert labels at set intervals). I found 1 second to be perfect, not too long to spoil and not too short to not be able to understand anything. Obviously I've cut off the end parts where it's basically silent void else nobody will figure out anything. That said, it's manual work and can have some errors, I don't have time to check through thousands of files. 2. I rename all those files in numerical order, from oldest to newest. I process songs in their track # order, so track 1 will be assigned the first numbers, track 2 will assign numbers after. Meaning snippets next to each other will be in order of the number. It's also how I keep track of which song is which number (for example Hello Seattle will correspond to 50-250.mp3). So, if the bot is playing file 153.mp3 and you don't know what that is, you can playback 152 or 154, the numbers next to it to figure out the clues. Since the file names are basically numbers I could convert them to numbers then have a command that basically playback +/- 2 or 3 numbers, but that's prob a lot of work. EDIT2: upon further inspections, I found out audacity was processing them too fast, leading some of the snippets to be out of order, so the above no longer hold true. However, the song name that I have on files should still be accurate. If I had named my files as numbers instead of abbreviated titles then I didn't have to sort by time, which leads to this inaccuracy. 3. I have an array that lists all those files and the code randomizes it when you issue the command. Then the bot plays that file. I added a new command that repeats the last selection so hopefully it works (it's been tested a total of 3 times by me lol). (edited)
